<F P=100> WEST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Narcotics Roundup for 28 April-5 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Narcotics Roundup for 28 April-5 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0505044694 </F>
<F P=103> LD0505044694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
fileworthy reports from 28 April-5 May on antinarcotics 
operations in countries monitored by FBIS London Bureau. 
Sources are given in parentheses at the end of each report. 
<H5>  France </H5>
  French custom officers seized 15 kilos of heroin at Roissy 
airport in two separate seizures on 19 and 26 April. On both 
occasions the drug was hidden in boxes containing scientific 
equipment on its way to Africa. (Paris France-Inter Radio 
Network in French 1200 GMT 3 May 94) 
<H5>  Portugal </H5>
  Police in Portimao arrested seven people and seized about 
270 
doses of heroin, a car, household electric appliances, cameras, 
car radios, hi-fi equipment, watches, money, and gold. The 
operations followed antinarcotics investigations in Western 
Algarve last week. The police believe they have broken up two 
drug trafficking gangs that operated in the region. (Lisbon 
Radio Renascenca in Portuguese to Europe 1400 GMT 4 May 94) 
<H5>  Sweden </H5>
  On 2 May, customs officers in Ystad foiled a smuggling 
attempt by an Iranian arriving from Swinoujscie, Poland carrying 
2 kg of pure opium worth some 3 to 4 million Swedish 
crowns--approximately $370,000 to $500,000. Two days earlier a 
Polish citizen was arrested in Ystad after customs officers 
discovered 10 kg of amphetamines hidden in his car. Both 
smugglers face sentences of at least five years in prison. 
(Warsaw PAP in English 1909 GMT 2 May 94) 

</TEXT>

