<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> GEORGIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Prime Minister Says Drug Problem Becoming `National </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Prime Minister Says Drug Problem Becoming `National </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Disaster' 

<F P=102>   AU0305200294 Tbilisi SVOBODNAYA GRUZIYA in Russian 26 Apr 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU0305200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi SVOBODNAYA GRUZIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["BS-Press" report under rubric "According to Information </F>
From Correspondents and Information Agencies": "Drug Addiction 
in Georgia Is Assuming the Scale of a National Disaster"] 
  [Text] Drug addiction in Georgia is assuming the scale of 
a national disaster, stated Deputy Prime Minister Irakliy 
Menagarishvili at today's conference for the heads of law 
enforcement bodies. According to figures presented by him, 
there are more than 100,000 drug addicts in Georgia and 200,000 
people who are taking narcotic substances; these are principally 
young people aged between 16 and 30. Georgia is facing the 
serious threat of the development of the drugs business. During 
the first quarter of 1994, there were 290 registered cases of 
drugs being smuggled into the republic. According to 
Menagarishvili, the main suppliers of drugs today are 
Azerbaijan, Central Asia, India, Pakistan, and Singapore. 
Moreover, so-called South Ossetia has recently become a 
dangerous center for the narcotics business. The cultivation, 
processing, and sale of raw materials for "impure drugs" has 
become the main source of income for many residents there. 
  According to the deputy prime minister, the solution lies in 
the creation of the corresponding legislative base to combat 
drugs and the drugs business and also a national bureau for the 
struggle against drug addiction and the drugs business attached 
to the Ministry of Internal Affairs and rayon police 
departments. He believes that it is also essential to 
coordinate work in this direction with international services 
that are engaged in the fight against drugs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

