<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> UKRAINE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Committee Discusses Fight Against Drug Trafficking </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cabinet Committee Discusses Fight Against Drug Trafficking </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0705172394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1035 
GMT 7 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0705172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By UKRINFORM, KRIM-TASS correspondent Viktor Kovalenko] </F>
  [Text] Kiev, 7 May--A session of the national coordination 
council for the fight against drug addiction under the Cabinet 
of Ministers of Ukraine was held on 6 May, chaired by Deputy 
Prime Minister Valeriy Shmarov. It discussed the problems of 
fighting illegal drug trafficking in Ukraine. 
  The acutely urgent issue of controlling illegal production, 
transportation, sale, and use of narcotic substances in Ukraine, 
as well as problems relating to providing the relevant bodies 
fighting this type of crime with the necessary equipment and 
financing, were discussed with representatives from the 
Ministries of Health, Finances, Internal Affairs, Environmental 
Protection, Education, and other state institutions. 
  It was pointed out at the session, inter alia, that a 
shortage of funds allocated to the law enforcement bodies is 
weakening their actions to seize consignments of narcotics and 
arrest the persons carrying them. It was decided to submit for 
the consideration of the Cabinet of Ministers a proposal to 
allocate, in a separate paragraph in Ukraine's state budget, 
funds to fight the spread of narcotics and drug addiction. 
  Those taking part in the session agreed on the necessity to 
start developing, in conjunction with the Academy of Science of 
Ukraine and the relevant government departments, Ukrainian-built 
equipment to detect narcotic substances during customs 
inspections, and also anesthetizing medical preparations that do 
not induce narcotic dependence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

