<H3> <TI>   Report `Confirms' Baja California State Police Protecting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Report `Confirms' Baja California State Police Protecting </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Traffickers 

<F P=102>   94WB0036A Mexico City EXCELSIOR in Spanish 19 Apr 94 STATES 
Section pp 1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> 94WB0036A </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City EXCELSIOR </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Rocio Galvan] </F>
  [Text] Tijuana, Baja California [BC], 18 April--The PAN's 
[National Action Party] local congressional faction submitted a 
report to the state's governor, Ernesto Ruffo Appel, regarding 
the shooting that occurred in this town on 3 March. It declares 
that the State Judicial Police (PJE) have been implicated in the 
drug traffic "ever since Francisco Franco Rios was named head of 
the State Attorney General's Office." This claim was made today 
by Congressman Armando Ayon, a member of the legislative body's 
Justice Commission. 
  Armando Ayon added that the document confirms certain 
statements made by Mexico's ambassador in France and by the 
ex-attorney general of the republic, Ignacio Morales Lechuga, to 
the effect that "Baja California judicial agents are giving 
protection to the drug traffic." 
  The document sent to Ruffo Appel was ratified by the eight 
PAN congressmen in the present legislature, who explain: "Not 
all the Judicial Branch officials and agents are in collusion 
with the drug traffic." 
  The investigation was conducted after the shooting that 
occurred on 3 March at the La Mesa local branch office, where 
five persons were killed: an incident that has not yet been 
totally explained. According to the aforementioned report, PJE 
agents gave protection to at least one of the drug traffickers 
involved in the shooting on this town's Diaz Ordaz Boulevard. 
  For this reason, the congressmen requested that Ruffo Appel 
call for the resignation of Francisco Franco Rios, since the 
police collusion with the drug traffic has been proven. 
  The PJE commander detailed here, Jorge Alvarez Barriere, for 
his part, announced that 13 agents from the force had been 
dismissed within the past two weeks: five for showing positive 
results in the drug testing, and the other eight for "loss of 
confidence" in them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

