<AU>   JPRS-TDD-94-021-L </AU>
JPRS 
Narcotics 

<DATE1>  6 April 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CHINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Xinjiang Official Calls for Boosting Counternarcotics Effort </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Xinjiang Official Calls for Boosting Counternarcotics Effort </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94P30050A Urumqi XINJIANG RIBAO in Chinese 6 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> 94P30050A </F>
<F P=104>  Urumqi XINJIANG RIBAO </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Summary] On 4 April at the Xinjiang Autonomous Region 
counternarcotics meeting, Vice Chairman Wang Lequan emphasized 
the serious nature of Xinjiang's narcotics problem. He noted 
that the counternarcotics effort is an urgent, long-term 
proposition. 
  According to Wang, despite some successes during the past 
three years, cultivation and trafficking of drugs have not been 
eliminated, and Xinjiang has seen the number of counties and 
cities with a drug trafficking problem increase from 40 to 53. 
In addition, traffickers have become better organized and 
developed more extensive networks, and their methods have become 
increasingly devious. Therefore, Xinjiang must improve its 
counternarcotics propaganda, and the region will focus its 
counternarcotics effort on cases involving large sums of money, 
trafficking routes and hubs, and deeply-involved criminals. At 
the same time, Xinjiang will counter scattered and sporadic 
trafficking, uncovering traffickers through patterns of drug use 
and destroying underground trafficking networks. Wang also 
stressed the development of a counternarcotics responsibility 
system involving the registration of drug users. 

</TEXT>

