<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> SOUTH KOREA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pharmacists, Distributors Arrested for Illegal Drug Sales </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pharmacists, Distributors Arrested for Illegal Drug Sales </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1205064294 Seoul THE KOREA TIMES in English 12 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> SK1205064294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A dozen pharmacists and distributors of 
pharmaceutical products have been arrested for illegally selling 
large quantities of a potent painkiller causing strong 
hallucination to the public at huge profits. 
  The Seoul District Prosecutor's Office said yesterday that 
two medical doctors were also indicted without formal arrest on 
charges of violating the Pharmaceutical Law for helping 
distributors take the products out of hospital inventory. 
  According to state prosecutors, the 12 arrested allegedly 
engaged in the distribution of products containing nalbuphane 
HC1, hallucinating its users, from April last year through last 
month. 
  Initial investigations showed that the 12, mostly 
pharmaceutical company employees, distributed 22,000 ampules 
(one ampule contains 10 centiliters) of the injection drug which 
have a market value of 60-100 million won (750,000-1.2 million 
U.S. dollars). 
  The prosecutors said the drug, which is believed to bring 
reactions as powerful as methamphetamine, sells for about 
30,000-50,000 won per ampule, mostly to youths and drug addicts. 
  "The distributors worked clandestinely with doctors and 
pharmacists to gain access to large quantities of nalbuphane and 
sold them through organized networks run by hooligans," one 
prosecutor explained. 
  In one instance, the prosecutors said, Yi Sok-chae, a 
manager 
of a pharmaceutical company, purchased 11,800 ampules at 400-500 
won each and sold them to another distributor at 1,500-2,000 won. 
  "What is shocking about this case is that it involved 
organized groups of people who are well aware of the dangerous 
implications of administering the painkiller," one prosecutor 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

