<H4>    Chuan Denies Ploy To Discredit Opposition </H4>

<F P=102> BK1205050494 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 12 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BK1205050494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Chuan Likphai yesterday denied that 
drug allegations against Chat Thai MP for Nakhon Phanom Thanong 
Siriprichaphong were an attempt by the Government to discredit 
the Opposition following a recent threat from the Opposition to 
censure the Government. 
  Mr Chuan dismissed reports that a large number of 
politicians 
were known to be involved in the narcotics trade but conceded 
that some of the drug suspects were politicians. 
  The Prime Minister said legal action would be taken against 
any individual suspected of being involved in narcotics 
trafficking regardless of who he or she is if enough evidence 
could be found to substantiate the charges. 
  However, he said the Government could not reveal any 
U.S.-supplied information on drug traffickers to the media in 
Thailand to avoid defamation charges. 
  PM's Office Minister Thoetphong Chaiyanan, who is also 
chairman of the Government Parties Coordination Committee, said 
the allegations against Mr Thanong must be thoroughly checked 
before the House of Representatives can make further moves on Mr 
Thanong's case. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

