<H3> <TI>   Customs Developing Computer Intelligence System; Container </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Customs Developing Computer Intelligence System; Container </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Cargo   Main Target 

<F P=102> 94WD0352A London THE TIMES in English 5 Apr 94 p 7--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94WD0352A </F>
<F P=104>  London THE TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Stewart Tendler, crime </F>
correspondent: "Computer Link Will Trap Drug Smugglers"] 
  [Text] A computer intelligence system aimed at stifling 
massive drug and arms smuggling rackets using ports in Britain, 
France, Holland, Belgium and Germany is being developed by 
Customs officials. 
  The computer data base will hold intelligence on container 
cargoes, shipping and trading companies and smuggling trends. It 
will enable Customs officers to identify potential targets and 
alert search teams to be ready as ships dock. 
  Due to begin within four years, the computer would link 
British ports including Southampton, Felixstowe, Liverpool and 
London with Rotterdam, Antwerp, Le Havre, Hamburg and Bremen. 
  The link is an extension of an electronic mailing system 
with 
more than 200 terminals round Europe, and a container profile 
scheme being used in Britain and mainland Europe. The system is 
so successful that Dutch officials say they have a 50-75 per 
cent success rate with every container they search. 

</TEXT>

