<F P=101> SOUTH KOREA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arrested Philopon Smugglers Reportedly Aided by Kimpo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arrested Philopon Smugglers Reportedly Aided by Kimpo </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Customs   Employee 

<F P=102> 94P30052B </F>
<F P=103> 94P30052B </F>
<F P=104></F>

  CSO 

  [Editorial Report] The daily PUSAN ILBO's 30 March 1994 
edition on page 23 carried a report that the office of the Pusan 
District Prosecutor arrested six philopon [crystal 
methamphetamine] smugglers, including an overseas 
Chinese-Korean, Wang Chin-saeng, who is employed by Kimpo 
Airport Customs as an interpreter. Chong Yong-sok and Kim 
Kil-tae were among the six arrested. 
  According to the prosecutor's office, the leader, Chong 
Yong-sok, paid Wang four million won [approximately U.S. 
$50,000] to accompany Chong and Kim Kil-tae to Taipei, Taiwan 
and interpret for them. Chong purchased one kilogram of 
philopon for five billion won [approximately U.S. $6.25 million] 
in Taipei and returned to Korea through Kimpo International with 
the drug concealed in the clothes Kim was wearing. 
  The smugglers were arrested on 28 March while they were 
contacting drug dealers in the Namdaemun market areas in Seoul. 
The one kilogram of philopon was seized as evidence when they 
were arrested. 
  Along with scrutinizing the background of Chong's drug 
business, the prosecutor's office has expanded the investigation 
because of Wang's involvement. The investigators are looking 
into the customs office and its employees for possible 
involvement in drug trafficking. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-67278 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptdd022__l94043" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TDD-94-022-L </AU>
JPRS 
Narcotics 

<DATE1>  17 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> LAOS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Souban Salitthilat Chairs Meeting on Drug Control </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Souban Salitthilat Chairs Meeting on Drug Control </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1705064894 Vientiane Vitthayou Hengsat Radio Network in 
Lao 0500 GMT 17 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1705064894 </F>
<F P=104>  Vientiane Vitthayou Hengsat Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Lao </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A meeting to publicize a comprehensive plan for drug 
control for the period from now to the year 2000 was held in 
Vientiane on the morning of 16 May. The meeting was chaired by 
Souban Salitthilat, deputy minister of foreign affairs and 
chairman of the Lao National Committee for Narcotics Control. 
It was attended by (Ms. Amerera Haq-perera), representative of 
the United Nations Development Program, along with many 
representatives from 10 northern provinces and representatives 
of various ministries and departments concerned. 
  Souban Salitthilat noted drug addiction as a problem which 
seriously threatens the world society at present. He said: 
Drug addiction and trafficking have been widely expanded, thus 
bringing about an adverse effect to the world. It is considered 
a problem for which everyone must be jointly held responsible. 
The deputy minister of foreign affairs noted: The Government 
of the Lao People's Democratic Republic [LPDR] has regarded as 
an important task the reduction of supply of opium and other 
addictive plants. To achieve the said goal, the LPDR Government 
has utilized all sources of funds totaling some $28 million from 
various countries as well as from international organizations to 
implement four projects in five provinces in the northern 
region, such as the Pha Lavek project in Vientiane Province, the 
Lao-American project in Houa Phan Province, and the rural 
development projects in Xieng Khouang, Bokeo, and Luang Namtha 
Provinces. At the same time, the government implemented a 
strategy of persuading people who have earned their living on 
slash-and-burn cultivation to switch to plains land to do rice 
farming and plant other types of crops, which can bring about 
higher revenues. This strategy can also help preserve the 
environment. 
  Souban Salitthilat stressed: The Lao Government presently 
has been prepared to cooperate, through every possible means, 
with all countries and international organizations in solving 
this problem on the basis of the principles of respecting each 
other's independence, sovereignty, and territorial integrity and 
mutual benefit. In cooperating with the UN Commission on 
Narcotic Drugs, the Lao Government has adopted a comprehensive 
narcotics control plan for implementation for the period from 
now to the year 2000. Stipulated in the said plan are the 
urgent needs as noted in the government's strategic plan, 
policy, and (projects) for actual practice, including the 
gradual reduction of poppy plantation; the elimination of the 
planting of marijuana for commercial purposes; the reduction and 
control of narcotics demand; the suppression and control of 
illicit trading, production, and other illegal acts involving 
narcotics; and working in cooperation with the world in dealing 
with this problem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-67279 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptdd022__l94044" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TDD-94-022-L </AU>
JPRS 
Narcotics 

<DATE1>  17 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Enactment of Law To Prevent Money Laundering Planned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Enactment of Law To Prevent Money Laundering Planned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1705083794 Taipei CNA in English 0811 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1705083794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 17 (CNA) -- Taiwan is planning to enact 
a law to prevent money laundering, Justice Minister Ma Ying-Jeou 
said Tuesday [17 May]. 
  Ma made the statement while meeting with a delegation from 
the G-7 Financial Action Task Force (FATF), a group of 
regulators set up in 1989 by the Group of Seven industrial 
countries to fight cross-border financial crime. 
  Many industrial countries, including the United States, 
France, Britain, Australia, Italy, Holland, and Luxembourg, have 
passed legislation outlawing money laundering. 
  Ma said the Ministry of Justice will start to draft 
regulations soon in cooperation with the Ministry of Finance and 
the Central Bank of China to prevent laundering of criminal 
money from drug and other illegal dealings. 
  "The legislation is needed as Taiwan is playing an 
increasingly important role in global trade and financial 
exchanges," Ma noted. 
  Under the draft regulations, Taiwan will require banks to 
report suspicious transactions to government authorities. 
  The draft bill is expected to be completed by the end of 
this 
year, Ma said. 
  The FATF delegation, headed by John Gieve, British 
undersecretary of treasury, said the Paris-based organization 
initiated in the 1988 G-7 economic summit would provide 
counseling services for Taiwan to pass legislation against money 
laundering. 
  The group, composed of experts from America, Japan and 
Britain, arrived in Taipei Sunday to check Taiwan's progress in 
the fight against money laundering. They will depart Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

