<F P=100> NEAR EAST &amp; SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> INDIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Methaqualone Factory `Seized' in Bombay </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Methaqualone Factory `Seized' in Bombay </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94WD0354A Bombay THE TIMES OF INDIA in English 1 Apr 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> 94WD0354A </F>
<F P=104>  Bombay THE TIMES OF INDIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] Bombay, March 31--The narcotics cell of the Bombay 
police last week seized a massive factory manufacturing 
methaqualone from which the drug Mandrax is made. 
  This is the first time in India that such a large 
methaqualone factory has been seized, although experts believe 
that India is the largest producer of Mandrax. 
  According to the chief of the narcotics cell, DCP [Deputy 
Commissioner of Police] Rahul Sur, Mandrax tablets and 
methaqualone powder each weighing 100 kg and collectively valued 
at Rs 20 lakhs were seized from the factory along with a Maruti 
car. 
  The factory, masquerading as Ambala Organic Chemicals Pvt 
Ltd 
in an industrial estate in Kadhi, Mehsana district, Gujarat, was 
spread over 10,000 sq feet and had five boilers 12-feet high. It 
is believed to have been in operation for the past nine months. 
  Six persons were arrested in this connection: Nitin Khimji 
Bhanushali (33) of Neelam Nagar, Mulund; Nayan Jetha Bhimji 
Bhanushali (28) of Sarvodaya Nagar, Mulund; Harish Kantibhai 
Patel (35) of Nadiad, Gujarat, and Manehdra Singh Sandhu (41), 
Kinit Jayantilal Amin (33), Amit Jayantibhai Patel (26), all of 
Ahmedabad. 
  However, Prem Shetty, one of the biggest manufacturers of 
Mandrax tablets in India, who had advanced the money through 
hawala for the purchse of the factory, is believed to have fled 
India. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

