<H3> <TI>   Efforts Against Opium, Cannabis Cultivation Detailed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Efforts Against Opium, Cannabis Cultivation Detailed </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Situation in Meghalaya, Manipur Viewed </H4>

<F P=102> 94WD0356B Calcutta THE STATESMAN in English 12 Apr 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> 94WD0356B </F>
<F P=104>  Calcutta THE STATESMAN </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] In its attempt to check illicit opium cultivation in 
Meghalaya, where this practice is the most prevalent among all 
the seven north-eastern States, a team of officials of the 
Narcotics Control Bureau, Eastern Region, recently raided Badak 
village in the Mariyang circle of east Siang district. 
  They destroyed more than 400,000 of opium plants. The NCB 
[Narcotics Control Board] team, assisted by CRPF [Central 
Reserve Police Force] jawans, set on fire the plants spread over 
30 plots on April 4, said Mr S. Nag, assistant director of the 
Bureau, in Calcutta on Monday. 
  According to the Union Finance Ministry sources, opium 
cultivation is rampant in east Siang and Lohit districts of 
Arunachal Pradesh for quite some time. 
  Apart from opium, another alarming trend is the massive 
cultivation of high-quality ganja in the Ukhrul and Senapati 
districts of Manipur which fetches Rs 1,500 and above a kg. 
  A major haul of about 1.5 tons of Manipur ganja in Calcutta 
in December last by the NCB is an eye-opener. 

</TEXT>

