<H3> <TI>   Kohl, Lintner Oppose `Release' of Small Amounts of Heroin, </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kohl, Lintner Oppose `Release' of Small Amounts of Heroin, </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Cocaine 

<F P=102>   AU1705103494 Hamburg DPA in German 0832 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1705103494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- On Tuesday [17 May] the coalition 
meeting, headed by Chancellor Helmut Kohl, clearly came out 
against the release of so-called hard drugs and thus against the 
line of North Rhine-Westphalian Justice Minister Rolf Krumsiek 
(Social Democratic Party of Germany). After the meeting 
Government Spokesman Dieter Vogel stated that the coalition 
agreed that the Anti-Crime Law should be adopted as quickly as 
possible. This law is to be discussed at its third hearing in 
the Bundestag this week. 
  Among other things, the coalition politicians discussed drug 
policy after the ruling of the Constitutional Court that, even 
though the possession of small amounts of cannabis products, 
such as hashish and marijuana is not permitted, criminal 
prosecution of such cases should be left to the discretion of 
the public prosecutor's offices. In Krumsiek's view, this 
ruling by the judges in Karlsruhe also covers his plan to no 
longer make the possession of small amounts of heroin and 
cocaine liable to criminal prosecution. This has been opposed, 
above all, by Internal Affairs State Secretary Eduard Lintner 
(Christian Social Union), the Federal Government's drug expert. 

